    "what_description": "Thyridolepis mitchelliana is a species of perennial grass in the family Poaceae. It is a tufted to erect plant that grows to a height of 20-100 cm, with a leafy culm (stem) and a flat, broad leaf blade that is 1-5 mm wide and has a prominent midrib. The inflorescence is a panicle, typically 10-30 cm long, with spikelets (small flower clusters) that are 5-10 mm long and have two fertile florets and one or two sterile florets. The plant has a short rhizome and produces new shoots from the base, and its roots are fibrous and adventitious. Thyridolepis mitchelliana is native to the southwestern region of Western Australia.",
